<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="111" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="111">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="111">
The type and other material identified as 
<taxonomicName authority="subsp. porteri" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" infraspecific-rank="subsp." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa juncifolia" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="juncifolia" subspecies="porteri">Poa juncifolia subsp. porteri</taxonomicName>
by Keck combine pubescent lemmas with narrow panicles, firm blades and short ligules on lateral shoots and appear to RJS to be intermediate in form between varieties 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="juncifolia" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="juncifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="111">juncifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="subsp. juncifolia (Scribn.) Soreng, Phytologia 71 (5): 401. 1991 b" authorityYear="1992" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="secunda" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="secunda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="111">secunda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="canbyi" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="canbyi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="111">canbyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
form).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="111" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="111">Habitat and range.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="111">
Pine forests and steppe, riparian and alkali meadows, in well-drained to poorly-drained, light to heavy, often alkaline or saline soils. Range of the subspecies (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Distribution of Poa secunda subspecies in North America: subsp. secunda (yellow); subsp. juncifolia (blue)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.110.27750.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/240277" pageId="10" pageNumber="111">2B</figureCitation>
), but infrequent in the California Floristic Province and south-western states.
</paragraph>
